# Analyzing World Development Indicators With Zeppelin/Hive/MapReduce/HDFS Tech Stack
In this project, we explore the fundementals of big data analytics in the Hadoop ecosystem. We walk through the workflow of importing data into a Hadoop Distributed File System, designing table schema for optimal query performance, and examining World Development Indicator data via Hive Query Language commands that can be interpreted by Apache Hive into tasks understood by the MapReduce execution engine.

The Hadoop cluster used in this project consists of one namenode, and two data nodes.

## Row Counting Performance Comparison: Bash Vs. Hive
Without data caching, querying the number of records in the table using Hive took 40+ seconds.
Conversely, obtaining the same information using the shell commands below produces results in half
the time (~17 seconds).

The difference in the two approaches is that with Hive, the results computed at each worker node must be transmitted
through networking protocals and aggregated, introducing communication latencies. On the other hand, the shell command
approach is working with the data stored locally, meaning no information needs to be exchanged among machines to perform
the row count. 

Also, there is an entire application stack that Hive must go through so that the rows in the table can
be counted; SQL-like Hive commands must be converted to execution tasks that YARN can understand, and then JVMs must
be spun up on worker nodes to run these tasks. Conversely, when we store the table in a local directory and use bash commands,
the code that actually does the row counting is immediately executed.

Nonetheless, the bash approach is not scalable for very large files, nor for managing a collection of very large files that cannot fit on a single machine. Moreover, when files are large, the paralellized computation across worker nodes begins to yield enough performance gains for the overhead of managing a data cluster to be worth it.

## A Parsing Issue
The below query that returns the first 20 sorted/distinct indicator nodes in the table produces unexpected results.
It appears as though portions of the indicator name field get placed into the field instead.

This is happening because we were using commas to delimit the different fields in the rows of data in the table, but the fields themselves
have commas in them, so when Hive constructed the table, it interpreted instances of commas present in the "indicator name" field as an
indication that it was time to start populating the next field in the table with the text coming after the comma.

## OpenCSVSerde to the Rescue
OpenCSVSerde was designed to provide csv support to Hive. [An open source project](https://github.com/ogrodnek/csv-serde) was adopted by the [Hive distribution](https://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/Hive/CSV+Serde) as OpenCSVSerde.

It provides support for specifying separator, quote, and escape characters needed to parse CSV files. The default character for the quote character is ", which is what our CSV data used to treat the fourth column of data as a single string, escaping special characters like commmas so they are ignored in the delimitation process.

%md
## Le Parquet
The Parquet file format is a column-oriented binary file format. This means in comparison to Plaintext, the table data can be represented with fewer bits, which means it will be faster to read/write the table information to/from disk/memory. Also, Parquet takes advantage of how Hive reads table data row-by-row, which is normally inefficient if you want to select a single column from the table because it must load the entire table and then parse the one field value you want from each row. The column-oriented nature of Parquet syntactically represents each logical column in the data table as a row, so Hive only needs to read the "rows" that contain the columns it needs for a query.

## Comparing Runtime: Parquet Vs. Plaintext
Below, we run two queries both on the Parquet file and the Plaintext file to compare their runtimes. The first query measures the size of the table, and the second query is the same GDP query ran previously. The Parquet table was able to count the number of rows in the table about 2.5 times faster than the Plaintext table, and ran the GDP query nearly 8 times faster.

The reason why the Parquet table outperformed the Plaintext file in general is that the more compact representation of the data takes less time to read from disk into memory. The reason why the Parquet table outperformed the Plaintext file to a greater extent for the GDP query lies within the column-oriented nature of the Parquet file format. In the Parquet file, the columns are actually represented as rows in the file, meaning Hive can skip entire columns of data despite having to read things "row by row". Thus, the process of filtering the data by the column criteria specified in the `WHERE` clause is faster, because Hive can look at the three columns it cares about (countryname, year, indicator code), find the single record that satisfies the `WHERE` condition, and return all the other fields for that single record.
